  "local_port": 34208,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the best way to clean ears?",
  "response": "Cleaning your ears properly is important for maintaining good ear health. Here are some recommended steps and tips:\n\n### 1. **Avoid Using Cotton Swabs Inside the Ear Canal**\n   - Cotton swabs (like Q-tips) can push earwax deeper into the ear canal, potentially leading to impaction or damage to the eardrum. They should only be used on the outer ear.\n\n### 2. **Use a Washcloth**\n   - After showering or bathing, gently wipe the outer ear with a washcloth. This can help remove any excess wax that has migrated to the outer ear.\n\n### 3. **Over-the-Counter Ear Drops**\n   - If you feel your ears are particularly waxy, over-the-counter ear drops can help soften the wax, making it easier to naturally expel. Follow the product instructions carefully.\n\n### 4. **Ear Irrigation**\n   - If you have a buildup of earwax, you can try ear irrigation. Use a rubber-bulb syringe to gently squirt warm (not hot) water into your ear canal. Tilt your head and pull the outer ear up and back to straighten the canal. Let the water sit for a moment, then tilt your head to let it drain out. Do not use this method if you have diabetes, a weakened immune system, or a hole in your eardrum, as it can lead to infection or other complications.\n\n### 5. **Professional Cleaning**\n   - If home methods don\u2019t work or if you experience symptoms like hearing loss, ear pain, or a feeling of fullness in your ear, see a healthcare professional. They can safely remove earwax and check for any underlying issues.\n\n### Additional Tips:\n- **Avoid Ear Candles**: Ear candling is not recommended as it can cause burns and does not effectively remove earwax.\n- **Don\u2019t Overdo It**: Earwax is a natural protectant for your ears, so avoid over-cleaning, which can lead to irritation or infection.\n\nBy following these guidelines, you can maintain clean and healthy ears without causing harm.",
